{{distinguish|Mercury (disambiguation){{!}}Mercury}} [[File:Mercerie bonneterie --Romanceor.jpg|thumb|450px|A mercery (mercer's shop) in Brussels]] '''Mercery''' (from French ''mercerie'', the [[Notions (sewing)|notions]] trade) initially referred to [[silk]], [[linen]], and [[fustian]] textiles imported to [[England]] in the 12th century.<ref>The Mercery of London, Anne F. Sutton, pg. 2</ref>
The term [[wikt:mercery|mercery]] later extended to goods made of these and the sellers of those goods.
==Mercer== The term [[wikt:mercer|'''mercer''']] for cloth merchants (from French ''mercier'', "notions dealer") is now largely obsolete. Mercers were formerly merchants or traders who dealt in cloth, typically fine cloth that was not produced locally. Inventories of mercers in small towns, however, suggest that many were shopkeepers who dealt in various dry commodities other than cloth.<ref>Europe's Rich Fabric: The Consumption, Commercialisation, and Production of Luxury Textiles in Italy, the Low Countries and Neighbouring Territories (Fourteenth-Sixteenth Centuries.) pp. 24–25.</ref> Related occupations include [[haberdasher]], [[draper]] and [[cloth merchant]], while [[cloth merchant|clothier]] historically referred to someone who manufactured [[cloth production|cloth]], often under the [[domestic system]].
By the 21st century the word ''mercer'' was primarily used in connection with the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers]], one of the twelve great [[Livery company|Livery Companies]] of the [[City of London]].
==Prominent mercers== * [[Wynne Ellis]], 19th century British mercer * [[Geoffrey Boleyn]], 15th century English mercer * [[Richard le Lacer]], 14th century English mercer * [[Charles Woodmason]]
